<tr id="L53"><td><a href="#L53">53</a></td><td>AMANDA:  Of course. He's a Vulcan. I'm his wife.</td></tr>

<tr id="L54"><td><a href="#L54">54</a></td><td>KIRK:  And Spock is his son.</td></tr>

<tr id="L55"><td><a href="#L55">55</a></td><td>AMANDA:  You don't understand the Vulcan way, Captain. It's logical. It's a better way than ours. But it's not easy. It has kept Spock and Sarek from speaking as father and son for eighteen years.</td></tr>

<tr id="L56"><td><a href="#L56">56</a></td><td>KIRK:  Spock is my best officer, and my friend.</td></tr>

<tr id="L57"><td><a href="#L57">57</a></td><td>AMANDA:  I'm glad he has such a friend. It hasn't been easy on Spock. Neither human nor Vulcan. At home nowhere except Starfleet.</td></tr>

<tr id="L58"><td><a href="#L58">58</a></td><td>KIRK:  I take it that Spock disagreed with his father on a choice of career.</td></tr>

<tr id="L59"><td><a href="#L59">59</a></td><td>AMANDA:  My husband has nothing against Starfleet. But Vulcans believe that peace should not depend on force.</td></tr>

<tr id="L60"><td><a href="#L60">60</a></td><td>KIRK:  Starfleet force is used only as a last resort. We're an instrument of civilisation. And it's a better opportunity for a scientist to study the universe than he can get at the Vulcan Science Academy.</td></tr>

<tr id="L61"><td><a href="#L61">61</a></td><td>AMANDA:  Perhaps. But Sarek wanted Spock to follow his teachings, as Sarek followed the teachings of his own father.</td></tr>

<tr id="L62"><td><a href="#L62">62</a></td><td>KIRK:  They are both stubborn.</td></tr>

<tr id="L63"><td><a href="#L63">63</a></td><td>AMANDA:  A human trait, Captain?</td></tr>

